20:26.158 --> 20:29.494 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Does this then conform to your
understanding
of how they operate?

20:29.528 --> 20:31.029 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN SIPHER, Former CIA Officer:
Well, certainly,
it does.

20:31.063 --> 20:36.702 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And this institute was actually
an internal
part of the SVR, the former KGB.

20:36.735 --> 20:39.438 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: This is not
some separate
think tank, like we would think
of in the

20:39.471 --> 20:41.206 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
U.S.?

20:41.240 --> 20:43.842 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN SIPHER: No, it was an
internal sort of
analytical unit, which then
separated and

20:43.875 --> 20:49.281 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
tied itself to the presidential
administration,
headed by longtime-serving KGB
officers.

20:49.314 --> 20:54.920 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In fact, the head of it now was
in fact the
head of the SVR, which is their
external intelligence

20:54.953 --> 20:56.955 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
service.

20:56.989 --> 21:00.692 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Is this the
kind of evidence,
John Sipher, that gave U.S.
intelligence agencies

21:00.726 --> 21:04.363 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the confidence to say, we think
Russia did
meddle in the election?

21:04.396 --> 21:07.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN SIPHER: I think this is
another piece
in that puzzle certainly.

21:07.799 --> 21:10.569 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
I don't think it's a big
surprise.

21:10.602 --> 21:15.407 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
President Putin hardly needed
this group to
tell him by June of 2016 that he
should start

21:15.440 --> 21:21.413 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
trying to influence the election
or to, you
know, find a candidate that was
pro-Russian,

21:21.446 --> 21:24.650 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
when we already by that time,
all of us sort
of knew that.

21:24.683 --> 21:31.590 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
However, I think the -- I do
think this is
part and parcel of a longer
effort that we

21:31.623 --> 21:33.425 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
see now in Europe.

21:33.458 --> 21:37.195 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, the Russians are now trying
to influence
elections in Germany and Russia
and in Bulgaria.

21:37.229 --> 21:43.101 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, in fact, Mr. Reshetnikov,
who ran this
institute, is tied to possible
efforts to

21:43.135 --> 21:45.837 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
assassinate the Montenegrin
prime minister
in Montenegro.

21:45.871 --> 21:49.107 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that may be, in fact, why he
lost his
job in January.

21:49.141 --> 21:54.780 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Ned Parker, in
these two
documents, as you have
discovered them, was

21:54.813 --> 21:59.818 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
there any mention of WikiLeaks
or the computer
hacking that intelligence
agencies also believe

21:59.851 --> 22:01.720 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the Russians were involved in?

22:01.753 --> 22:06.291 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NED PARKER: No, there is no
mention of WikiLeaks
or the hacking, but I think you
have to see

22:06.325 --> 22:12.030 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
these as they were described to
myself and
my colleagues, John Walcott and
Jon Landay.

22:12.064 --> 22:15.067 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They were described as part and
parcel of
a campaign.

22:15.100 --> 22:20.372 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, the Kremlin is a very
top-down, authoritarian
culture.

22:20.405 --> 22:25.243 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So when these documents passed
around, they
only reinforced what everyone
knew to do.

22:25.277 --> 22:31.817 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, when you actually started to
see the WikiLeaks
dumps happening, the
Russian-affiliated media

22:31.850 --> 22:37.889 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
outlets, like U.S. -- like
Russia Today and
Sputnik and the troll factories
outside of

22:37.923 --> 22:44.296 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
St. Petersburg that pump news
out on Twitter
and other outlets on the
Internet, they were

22:44.329 --> 22:51.737 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
able to amplify the voice and
the reach of
the hacked, stolen materials
from the Clinton

22:51.770 --> 22:53.038 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
campaign and DNC.

22:53.071 --> 22:55.040 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, they reinforced each other.

22:55.073 --> 22:59.778 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: John Sipher,
is it really
that easy for the Russian
government to say,

22:59.811 --> 23:04.816 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you three news agencies, start
pumping out
stories that are anti-Clinton or
pro-Trump?

23:04.850 --> 23:06.785 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Is that -- does it work that
obviously?

23:06.818 --> 23:10.555 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN SIPHER: It's funny because,
in my time
in government, especially in the
last years,

23:10.589 --> 23:14.259 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
we often talked about an
all-of-government
approach, so, if we're going
into Afghanistan,

23:14.292 --> 23:16.928 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
all of our agencies and
institutes had to
work together.

23:16.962 --> 23:20.365 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have never been quite as good
at it as
the Russians, because that's a
centralized

23:20.399 --> 23:22.100 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
state.

23:22.134 --> 23:25.837 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the intelligence services,
from which
Mr. Putin came, were the central
sword and

23:25.871 --> 23:27.672 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
shield of the government.

23:27.706 --> 23:32.577 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, therefore, yes, they do a
very good job
of a coordinated approach to use
diplomatic,

23:32.611 --> 23:35.881 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
intelligence, military and
political power
as one.

23:35.914 --> 23:37.849 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, I'm not surprised at all by
this.

23:37.883 --> 23:42.087 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Ned, you heard
John mention
earlier that the concern
obviously is that

23:42.120 --> 23:44.823 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the Russians, they did it to us
back in 2016.

23:44.856 --> 23:48.093 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We have elections coming up in
France and
elsewhere in Europe.

23:48.126 --> 23:52.264 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Did the intelligence officials
that you talked
with for this reporting, did
they give you

23:52.297 --> 23:55.700 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
any sense that they believe that
the Russians
are going to be involved in
those elections

23:55.734 --> 23:56.935 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
as well?

23:56.968 --> 24:00.105 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NED PARKER: I think that's sort
of -- it's
an open secret.

24:00.138 --> 24:01.807 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Right?

24:01.840 --> 24:05.510 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You look at France, and Marine
Le Pen makes
no secret of her affection for
Russia.

24:05.544 --> 24:09.815 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, I think that's seen as part
and parcel
for the course.

24:09.848 --> 24:12.818 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: John Sipher,
one last question
before you go.

24:12.851 --> 24:17.088 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I understanding there is --
there's also reporting
about a mole hunt that is going
on within

24:17.122 --> 24:19.257 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the CIA right now.

24:19.291 --> 24:21.593 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
From your time in the CIA, what
can you tell
us about that?

24:21.626 --> 24:23.662 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JOHN SIPHER: Yes, that's
unfortunate.

24:23.695 --> 24:27.532 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Any organization or enterprise
has to worry
about the insider threat and
this type of

24:27.566 --> 24:29.734 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
thing happening, to include the
CIA.

24:29.768 --> 24:34.606 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In my time in government, I have
seen, and
we have caught spies, like
Aldrich Ames and

24:34.639 --> 24:36.508 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Hanssen at the FBI.

24:36.541 --> 24:42.481 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Almost always in that case, it
is an intelligence
source of ours that lead us to
find out who

24:42.514 --> 24:44.182 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
that person is.

24:44.216 --> 24:48.220 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I wish them the best of luck
in figuring
this out, and hopefully they can
find out

24:48.253 --> 24:49.955 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
who it is before too long,
certainly.

24:49.988 --> 24:53.391 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: All right,
John Sipher,
Ned Parker of Reuters, thank you
both very

24:53.425 --> 24:56.161 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
much for being here.

24:56.194 --> 25:02.667 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JOHN SIPHER: Thanks.

25:02.701 --> 25:07.606 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Stay with us.

