25:47.479 --> 25:53.618 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Marcus Huey, Ken
Block, and Delia
Salvatierra all live in the
Phoenix area and

25:53.652 --> 25:56.087 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
call themselves news junkies.

25:56.121 --> 25:59.057 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But that's where the similarity
ends.

25:59.090 --> 26:05.163 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Their sources of news are as
different as
their politics.

26:05.196 --> 26:07.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Salvatierra is a Democrat who
voted for Hillary
Clinton.

26:07.899 --> 26:12.804 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DELIA SALVATIERRA, Democrat: The
New York
Times, The Washington Post, CNN,
and "The

26:12.837 --> 26:17.576 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
New Yorker" are sort of the
foundational things
that I surround myself with.

26:17.609 --> 26:21.112 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Huey is a Republican
who voted
for President Trump.

26:21.146 --> 26:25.617 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCUS HUEY, Republican: As a
voting member
of the Republican Party, I would
say anything

26:25.650 --> 26:29.387 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that comes out of FOX, I pretty
much take
to the bank.

26:29.421 --> 26:33.224 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If something comes from Laura
Ingraham, I
pretty much take that to the
bank.

26:33.258 --> 26:37.963 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JOHN YANG: And Block, an
independent, voted
for Libertarian candidate Gary
Johnson.

26:37.996 --> 26:40.699 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KEN BLOCK, Independent: I kind
of bounce all
over the board.

26:40.732 --> 26:44.903 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I have Twitter and a news feed
on my phone.

26:44.936 --> 26:48.607 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, you know, I take a little
bit of everything.

26:48.640 --> 26:53.712 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JOHN YANG: None of that
surprises Thom Reilly,
director of the nonpartisan
Morrison Institute

26:53.745 --> 26:57.215 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
for Public Policy at Arizona
State University.

26:57.248 --> 27:02.220 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He's one of the authors of new a
study examining
where voters get both news and
commentary.

27:02.253 --> 27:05.357 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
THOM REILLY, Director, Morrison
Institute
for Public Policy: Well, voters
today basically

27:05.390 --> 27:11.229 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
have this cafeteria type format,
where they
can choose from personalized
news sources

27:11.262 --> 27:16.668 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that not only serves to inform
them, but also
reinforces their world view.

27:16.701 --> 27:21.473 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We want to hear stuff that we
believe in,
or just kind of particularly in
a very polarized

27:21.506 --> 27:23.074 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
world.

27:23.108 --> 27:26.344 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, I do think we're seeing
this, people going
back to what -- they feel safe.

27:26.378 --> 27:32.050 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: The researchers found
that the
proliferation of news sources on
cable TV

27:32.083 --> 27:38.289 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and the Internet has upended the
relationship
between news outlets and their
audiences.

27:38.323 --> 27:44.496 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Instead of voters being shaped
by news, Reilly
says news is being shaped for
voters.

27:44.529 --> 27:50.101 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
THOM REILLY: What we're seeing
is that, particularly
with a lot of Internet sources,
is they're

27:50.135 --> 27:54.406 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
appealing to a base, and they're
attracting
a wide audience, and it's
growing.

27:54.439 --> 27:59.077 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And they're responding to what
voters want,
instead of vice versa.

27:59.110 --> 28:03.481 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: It used to be that
politicians
and candidates would appeal to a
base, but

28:03.515 --> 28:06.351 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
now you're saying that news
outlets are appealing
to their base?

28:06.384 --> 28:08.553 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
THOM REILLY: And they're shaping
it, yes,
yes.

28:08.586 --> 28:13.458 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Democrat Salvatierra
grew up in
a conservative Republican
household and found

28:13.491 --> 28:17.796 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
her own brand of politics in
college at the
University of California,
Berkeley.

28:17.829 --> 28:22.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She now runs her own immigration
and criminal
law practice.

28:22.434 --> 28:26.938 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DELIA SALVATIERRA: I think the
press has become
increasingly important.

28:26.971 --> 28:34.512 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And I think once the new
administration attacked
certain organizations as fake
news, it only

28:34.546 --> 28:40.185 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
empowered me to listen to those
news organizations
even more.

28:40.218 --> 28:48.093 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And whereas before I could flip
back and forth
between maybe FOX News and CNN,
I don't trust

28:48.126 --> 28:51.596 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
FOX News, because it is so
overwhelmingly
endorsed by the administration.

28:51.629 --> 28:59.604 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JOHN YANG: But you're
deliberately seeking
out opinions, commentary that
reinforce your

28:59.637 --> 29:00.605 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
