34:02.507 --> 34:15.620 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: The airline
industry and
its business model have been in
the crosshairs

34:15.653 --> 34:20.391 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of late, particularly since the
United Airlines
story captured worldwide
attention.

34:20.425 --> 34:25.129 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Many travelers have been asking,
how do airlines
make money, and do those profits
come at the

34:25.163 --> 34:28.032 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
expense of passenger comfort and
convenience?

34:28.066 --> 34:31.235 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Our economics correspondent,
Paul Solman,
has been exploring the turbulent
business

34:31.269 --> 34:32.637 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of aviation.

34:32.670 --> 34:36.007 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
It's part of his weekly
reporting on Making
Sense of economic news.

34:36.040 --> 34:37.408 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
WOMAN: Oh, my God!

34:37.442 --> 34:39.177 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
WOMAN: Oh, my God.

34:39.210 --> 34:43.815 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: The whole world was
watching,
watching United Airlines last
week, as its

34:43.848 --> 34:47.485 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
skies proved a lot less friendly
than advertised.

34:47.518 --> 34:52.590 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But a flight we took recently
had a much happier
ending: No passenger was
bloodied and dragged

34:52.623 --> 34:57.962 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
from the plane, which took off
from tiny Windsor
Locks, Connecticut, and landed
barely five

34:57.995 --> 35:05.670 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
hours later in Dublin, Ireland,
for an affordable
$549 round-trip, including
four-day hotel

35:05.703 --> 35:07.672 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
stay for some of the passengers.

35:07.705 --> 35:13.644 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There's a larger theme of our
story, however,
that an industry notorious for
losing money

35:13.678 --> 35:20.051 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
has been making it, hand over
fist, at the
expense of often helpless
consumers, but that

35:20.084 --> 35:23.521 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
competition may be on the verge
of rescuing
us at long last.

35:23.554 --> 35:27.592 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEPHEN KAVANAGH, CEO, Aer
Lingus: The president
was kind enough to put knots in
this twine.

35:27.625 --> 35:32.530 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Aer Lingus CEO
Stephen Kavanagh
keeps an old globe gifted to his
predecessor

35:32.563 --> 35:35.266 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in the 1960s by the president of
Ireland.

35:35.299 --> 35:39.737 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEPHEN KAVANAGH: The first knot
being based
in Ireland, and the second knot
was the technical

35:39.770 --> 35:42.707 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
range of aircraft at the time.

35:42.740 --> 35:46.344 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And his ambition was that
Ireland would become
a gateway point.

35:46.377 --> 35:50.081 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And 50 years later, we believe
we're delivering
on that ambition.

35:50.114 --> 35:54.619 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Now, Aer Lingus
wasn't exactly
a cash cow as a government
service.

35:54.652 --> 35:58.322 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Aer Lingus was owned by the
Irish government
up until when?

35:58.356 --> 35:59.557 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
STEPHEN KAVANAGH: 2006.

35:59.590 --> 36:04.061 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: And it lost money
in all that
time, right?

36:04.095 --> 36:05.129 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
STEPHEN KAVANAGH: Yes.

36:05.163 --> 36:07.031 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Well, most of the time, yes.

36:07.064 --> 36:11.402 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
PAUL SOLMAN: When I told
sophisticated business
people that I was doing this
story, they said,

36:11.435 --> 36:15.339 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
oh, airlines, an industry that
always in the
end loses money.

36:15.373 --> 36:23.581 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, are you just in a up phase
of what eventually
is going to be a down industry?

36:23.614 --> 36:28.119 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
STEPHEN KAVANAGH: There's no
doubt that the
business is cyclical.

36:28.152 --> 36:33.191 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And there's no doubt that that
industry over
many years has had difficulty in
returning

36:33.224 --> 36:34.725 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
its cost of capital to
shareholders.

36:34.759 --> 36:36.794 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: By difficulty, you
mean it hasn't.

36:36.827 --> 36:38.696 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
STEPHEN KAVANAGH: It hasn't.

36:38.729 --> 36:43.067 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: But smaller,
fuel-efficient planes
can now reach well beyond the
knot on that

36:43.100 --> 36:44.902 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
1960s string.

36:44.936 --> 36:50.508 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Indeed, these are boom times for
airlines,
and not just Aer Lingus.

36:50.541 --> 36:52.410 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What explains the turnaround?

36:52.443 --> 36:56.948 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The answer demands a bit of
ancient history
and ancient footage as well.

36:56.981 --> 37:01.953 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For decades, governments,
including the U.S.,
strictly regulated fares and
routes, if they

37:01.986 --> 37:04.255 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
didn't own the carriers
outright.

37:04.288 --> 37:08.759 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Fares worldwide were high,
routes plentiful,
planes often half-empty.

37:08.793 --> 37:12.096 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
But profits were rare to
nonexistent.

37:12.129 --> 37:18.302 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Then, in 1977, President Jimmy
Carter anointed
Cornell economist Alfred Kahn to
deregulate.

37:18.336 --> 37:22.540 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALFRED KAHN, Economist: It's the
greatest
thing I ever did in my life,
other than have

37:22.573 --> 37:23.541 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
children.

37:23.574 --> 37:24.942 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

37:24.976 --> 37:27.578 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Kahn thought market
forces would
bring air travel to all.

37:27.612 --> 37:30.081 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He didn't worry much about
profits.

37:30.114 --> 37:34.352 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When I visited him in Ithaca,
New York, in
2003, he was proud of his
legacy.

37:34.385 --> 37:41.559 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALFRED KAHN: What I did has been
extraordinarily
beneficial to millions and
millions and millions

37:41.592 --> 37:46.564 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
of people every year who
couldn't afford to
travel, who now can visit their
grandparents,

37:46.597 --> 37:53.304 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
which now strikes home to me, go
home for
vacation from college, who can
travel and

37:53.337 --> 37:55.106 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
indeed can be tourists.

37:55.139 --> 38:01.545 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: But a key part of
Kahn's plan
never materialized: antitrust
enforcement.

38:01.579 --> 38:09.353 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Thus, deregulation spurred a
wave of mergers,
speeded up when business was
walloped by 9/11

38:09.387 --> 38:11.355 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and then the crash of '08.

38:11.389 --> 38:13.157 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Bankruptcies abounded.

38:13.190 --> 38:20.064 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Today, the U.S. fleet has shrunk
to just four
main carriers, which control 80
percent-plus

38:20.097 --> 38:21.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of the U.S. market.

38:21.999 --> 38:27.638 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
No wonder passengers are at the
mercy of the
major airlines: flights
jam-packed, routes

38:27.672 --> 38:30.641 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
slashed, service to smaller
airports dumped.

38:30.675 --> 38:37.682 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Yes, fares have dipped, but
costs have dipped
more, thanks to new planes,
cheap fuel, do-it-ourselves

38:37.715 --> 38:43.421 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
software, and union work
outsourced to contract
workers.

38:43.454 --> 38:50.928 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Meanwhile, fees have so
metastasized here
in the U.S., one low-cost
airline now differentiates

38:50.961 --> 38:52.330 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
itself by mocking them.

38:52.363 --> 38:54.265 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ACTOR: Is this your first
flight?

38:54.298 --> 38:57.802 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NARRATOR: On Southwest Airlines,
we don't
charge fees for stuff that
should be free.

38:57.835 --> 39:03.307 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: U.S. airlines alone
made an estimated
$20 billion last year.

39:03.341 --> 39:10.514 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Fees accounted for an estimated
$3.8 billion,
itinerary change charges another
$3 billion.

39:10.548 --> 39:15.086 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Selling miles to credit card
companies has
been estimated to bring in
upwards of $10

39:15.119 --> 39:16.620 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
