from Connecticut, as we flew
affordably to

41:08.933 --> 41:12.269 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Dublin.

41:12.303 --> 41:17.575 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
As we enjoy a brief pub
interlude, remember
the advantages of competition on
flights to

41:17.608 --> 41:26.050 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Dublin or anywhere else: low
fares, no fees,
comfy planes from which no one
is in danger

41:26.083 --> 41:29.954 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of forcible removal, because of
the profits
that beckon.

41:29.987 --> 41:32.523 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And one last time, why the
profits?

41:32.556 --> 41:35.826 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Two main reasons, claims Aer
Lingus CEO Kavanagh.

41:35.860 --> 41:41.499 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEPHEN KAVANAGH: That there has
been some
level of consolidation in North
America, where

41:41.532 --> 41:48.172 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it's possible for airlines as
businesses to
generate sustainable levels of
profitability.

41:48.205 --> 41:50.941 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the other is, capital is
more disciplined
as to where it's deployed.

41:50.975 --> 41:55.045 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Investors are more
disciplined,
he means, in that they now
demand immediate

41:55.079 --> 41:58.782 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
profits, or simply sell their
airline stocks.

41:58.816 --> 42:03.921 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But maybe the discipline in
North America
is just consolidation, right?

42:03.954 --> 42:11.061 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, it may be that if there
were more
vigorous pursuit of antitrust in
America,

42:11.095 --> 42:17.535 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you would have more competitors
competing
on price, and then airlines
wouldn't be making

42:17.568 --> 42:18.936 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
any money again.

42:18.969 --> 42:22.806 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Kavanagh's answer to this
question may be
the moral of this story.

42:22.840 --> 42:25.609 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
STEPHEN KAVANAGH: That is
undeniably true.

42:25.643 --> 42:33.884 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If you have full freedom of
access to a market,
where capital is cheap, where
there isn't

42:33.918 --> 42:37.354 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a discipline of a return, then
that isn't
a stable market.

42:37.388 --> 42:42.560 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, in airlines, no business in
that type
of environment is capable of
generating sustainable

42:42.593 --> 42:44.295 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
return.

42:44.328 --> 42:46.196 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Which would suggest
that, once
competition hits full-throttle,
consumers

42:46.230 --> 42:54.505 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
may then again be flying high,
while the airline
industry will be coming back
down to earth.

42:54.538 --> 43:01.679 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," Paul
Solman, reporting
from Dublin, Ireland, and 15
miles north of

43:01.712 --> 43:06.016 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Hartford, Connecticut.

43:06.050 --> 43:16.160 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Now: race,
crime and imprisonment.

43:16.193 --> 43:19.263 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That's the focus of the newest
addition to
the "NewsHour" Bookshelf.

43:19.296 --> 43:21.065 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Jeffrey Brown has that.

43:21.098 --> 43:25.069 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Mass
incarceration and its
devastating effect on black
Americans and

43:25.102 --> 43:29.506 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
neighborhoods, it's a subject
that's attracted
much attention in books and
policy circles

43:29.540 --> 43:31.175 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in the last decade.

43:31.208 --> 43:35.679 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A new take on the issue comes in
the book
"Locking Up Our Own: Crime and
Punishment

43:35.713 --> 43:41.151 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in Black America," based in part
on the experience
of author James Forman Jr. as a
public defender

43:41.185 --> 43:45.889 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in Washington, D.C. Forman is
now a professor
at Yale Law School and joins me
now

43:45.923 --> 43:47.658 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Welcome to you.

43:47.691 --> 43:48.025 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAMES FORMAN JR., Author,
"Locking Up Our
Own: Crime and Punishment in
Black America":

43:48.058 --> 43:49.560 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Thank you.

43:49.593 --> 43:51.095 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Let me pick up on
that experience
of being a public defender.

43:51.128 --> 43:54.231 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What did you see there that made
you rethink
the story of mass incarceration?

43:54.264 --> 43:59.336 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAMES FORMAN JR.: Well, I went
into the job
because I viewed this as the
civil rights

43:59.370 --> 44:03.907 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
issue of my generation, one in
three black
men under criminal justice
supervision.

44:03.941 --> 44:10.247 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And when I got to local courts
of Washington,
D.C., what I saw was case after
case with

44:10.280 --> 44:13.250 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
African-American judges,
prosecutors, bailiffs.

44:13.283 --> 44:19.523 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
D.C. has a significant
African-American representation
in operation of this criminal
justice system.

44:19.556 --> 44:21.592 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And that system was very harsh.

44:21.625 --> 44:26.363 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I had one case where a judge
before locking
up my client lectured him on
Martin Luther

44:26.397 --> 44:28.132 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
King.

44:28.165 --> 44:31.602 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He said, Martin Luther King
fought and died
for your generation to be free,
and you're

44:31.635 --> 44:37.708 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
out here messing it up, carrying
a gun, getting
high, disrespecting your family
and the neighborhood.

44:37.741 --> 44:40.744 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, that's the thing that really
told me there
was a story here.

44:40.778 --> 44:43.714 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: You know, a
number of books
and thinkers have looked as this
over the

44:43.747 --> 44:48.519 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
last number of years, mass
incarceration through
the lens on institutional
racism, right, even

44:48.552 --> 44:52.022 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a continuation of the history of
slavery in
this country.

44:52.056 --> 44:55.492 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Are you challenging the story,
filling it
in?

44:55.526 --> 44:57.061 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What do you see yourself doing
here?

44:57.094 --> 45:01.098 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JAMES FORMAN JR.: No, I think
that story is
correct and powerful and urgent.

45:01.131 --> 45:06.704 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, what I see what I'm doing is
adding to
it, because there's a part of
the story that

45:06.737 --> 45:08.672 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
we haven't focused on yet.

45:08.706 --> 45:13.343 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it's the part of the story
of this generation
of African-American
decision-makers that came

45:13.377 --> 45:18.282 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in at the end of the civil
rights movement
and took office, became police
chiefs, became

45:18.315 --> 45:20.050 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
prosecutors, became judges.

45:20.084 --> 45:21.251 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What were they doing during
the...

45:21.285 --> 45:22.386 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Became the
attorney general.

45:22.419 --> 45:23.387 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
You talk about Eric Holder.

45:23.420 --> 45:25.189 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JAMES FORMAN JR.: Absolutely,
who...

45:25.222 --> 45:29.359 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Give us an
example, though,
I mean, of what -- a specific
example, like

45:29.393 --> 45:31.095 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Holder?

45:31.128 --> 45:33.230 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAMES FORMAN JR.: Well, OK, so
somebody like
Eric Holder comes in as the U.S.
attorney

45:33.263 --> 45:38.268 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for the District of Columbia in
the early
1990s, and he gives a big speech
where he

45:38.302 --> 45:42.573 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
says, crime and violence are
destroying our
communities.

45:42.606 --> 45:48.612 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He says, the black people of
D.C. are no more
free than the black people of
Selma, Alabama,

45:48.645 --> 45:50.547 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
were in 1955.

45:50.581 --> 45:55.919 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But what's keeping us down,
what's keeping
us locked inside is crime and
violence and

45:55.953 --> 45:57.755 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
criminal gangs.

45:57.788 --> 46:03.093 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, in response to that, he
promoted a program
called Operation Cease-Fire,
where police

46:03.127 --> 46:10.033 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
would stop cars on any pretext,
of a minor
traffic violation, speeding,
tinted windows,

46:10.067 --> 46:13.303 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
you name it, because they wanted
to search
those cars for guns.

46:13.337 --> 46:18.709 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, with good
intention, the
best intentions, of protecting
the black community,

46:18.742 --> 46:23.347 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but you're suggesting all of
that helped foment
what's come in the mass
incarceration.

46:23.380 --> 46:25.149 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JAMES FORMAN JR.: Exactly.

46:25.182 --> 46:29.686 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, the story -- my story is
a tragedy,
right, because it is a story of
best intentions

46:29.720 --> 46:31.488 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in many cases.

46:31.522 --> 46:35.225 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You have people, often, they
don't -- part
of the story is that people
didn't know what

46:35.259 --> 46:36.727 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
was going to happen next.

46:36.760 --> 46:40.430 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, in the 1970s, they chose not
to decriminalize
marijuana.

46:40.464 --> 46:43.801 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That was a big debate in D.C. at
the time.

46:43.834 --> 46:45.569 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And when -- they didn't do it.

46:45.602 --> 46:49.506 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they said, well, it's not
that big of
a deal if we don't decriminalize
marijuana,

46:49.540 --> 46:54.611 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
because nobody's really going to
prison, no
one's losing their job for a
marijuana conviction.

46:54.645 --> 47:00.250 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But then, later in the '80s and
in the '90s,
we passed laws that said you
can't get a student

47:00.284 --> 47:05.355 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
loan, you can't get public
housing, you can't
get a job if you have a
marijuana conviction.

47:05.389 --> 47:10.961 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, a decision they made at time
A later turns
out to have these devastating
effects.

47:10.994 --> 47:15.032 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, when and why
did these
attitudes change?

47:15.065 --> 47:17.067 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Or have they shifted
sufficiently?

47:17.100 --> 47:19.336 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JAMES FORMAN JR.: Well, they
have shifted
in part.

47:19.369 --> 47:22.973 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I think the big thing that's
happened
in the last few years -- and the
Black Lives

47:23.006 --> 47:27.744 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Matter movement is a part of
this, important
writers like Michelle Alexander
and Bryan

47:27.778 --> 47:31.882 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Stevenson and Ta-Nehisi Coates
have really
promoted this issue.

47:31.915 --> 47:37.054 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And attitudes in the black
community have
started to change, as people
more and more

47:37.087 --> 47:41.091 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
see mass incarceration as a
racial justice
issue.

47:41.124 --> 47:47.464 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But one thing that hasn't
changed is, we still
don't really talk about people
who have committed

47:47.497 --> 47:49.266 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
violent crimes.

47:49.299 --> 47:54.538 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When we say we're going to try
to reduce mass
incarceration, our whole focus
so far has

47:54.571 --> 47:56.773 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
been on nonviolent drug
offenders.

47:56.807 --> 47:59.343 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I argue in the book, that's
not going
far enough.

47:59.376 --> 48:04.815 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Why is it
important to recognize
the role of African-Americans in
bringing

48:04.848 --> 48:06.583 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
about mass incarceration?

48:06.617 --> 48:12.155 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You know, why is it important to
fill in or
tell the story, take the story
further the

48:12.189 --> 48:13.957 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
way you have?

48:13.991 --> 48:17.127 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAMES FORMAN JR.: Well, part of
it, honestly,
is, you know, I'm just that kind
of person

48:17.160 --> 48:21.064 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
who, if I go to a movie, and
there's no black
characters, somebody asks me at
the end of

48:21.098 --> 48:23.834 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the movie, what did you think
about it, I
say, well, it was OK, but there
were -- there

48:23.867 --> 48:25.569 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
were no -- where were the black
characters?

48:25.602 --> 48:30.173 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, I think that black
people have been
central to every part of
American history.

48:30.207 --> 48:33.277 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so I don't want to watch a
movie, I don't
want to read a book, I don't
want to study

48:33.310 --> 48:37.948 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
history that doesn't show the
role that African-Americans
were playing.

48:37.981 --> 48:42.119 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, that, to me, is really, at a
basic level,
the number one reason.

48:42.152 --> 48:48.992 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But it's also because,
factually, we were
there, right, in D.C., in
Atlanta, in Memphis,

48:49.026 --> 48:51.828 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in Los Angeles, in Chicago, in
New York.

48:51.862 --> 48:54.798 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
You have substantial
African-American representation.

48:54.831 --> 48:57.567 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I just don't think we can
write us out
of the picture.

48:57.601 --> 49:00.337 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Let me ask you,
finally, I
mean, we started with a personal
story, you

49:00.370 --> 49:04.474 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
as a public defender, talking
about the unfinished
work of the civil rights
movement.

49:04.508 --> 49:09.546 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You're also the son of a very
prominent civil
rights leader, James Forman.

49:09.579 --> 49:15.018 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Connect the dots for me, the
kind of work
as a public defender, but, more
importantly,

49:15.052 --> 49:18.822 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the mass incarceration problem
now to the
civil rights movement.

49:18.855 --> 49:19.923 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
How do you see it?

49:19.957 --> 49:23.126 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JAMES FORMAN JR.: Well, they
have this similarity.

49:23.160 --> 49:29.499 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Both of them have -- that is to
say, Jim Crow
and mass incarceration both have
led to a

49:29.533 --> 49:35.205 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
whole part of the population
being locked
out of opportunity by being
defined by a certain

49:35.238 --> 49:39.409 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
status, either your race or the
fact that
you have a criminal conviction.

49:39.443 --> 49:45.048 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that means you can't get a
job, you can't
get public housing, you can't
get student

49:45.082 --> 49:48.819 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
loans, you can't live freely as
an American
citizen.

49:48.852 --> 49:54.458 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so I think, really, what the
civil rights
movement was about was finding
the most acute

49:54.491 --> 49:58.895 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
thing that was harming black
people, which
at the time was Jim Crow, and
responding.

49:58.929 --> 50:02.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I see the movement to fight
mass incarceration
in much the same way today.

50:02.399 --> 50:06.003 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: All right, the
new book is
"Locking Up Our Own: Crime and
Punishment

50:06.036 --> 50:07.637 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in Black America,"

50:07.671 --> 50:08.605 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
James Forman Jr., thank you very
much.

50:08.638 --> 50:12.309 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JAMES FORMAN JR.: Thank you.

